   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">That $60 trillion number is so large</span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1226421/50879105#c14?mode=alone;showrate=1#c14">31+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


<div class="crs"><dl>
  <dt>Recommended by:</dt><dd>
  <a href="/user/uid:31900">pat bunny</a>, <a href="/user/uid:167108">Puddytat</a>, <a href="/user/uid:167631">Egalitare</a>, <a href="/user/uid:1051">Superskepticalman</a>, <a href="/user/uid:79790">WarrenS</a>, <a href="/user/uid:335824">tuesdayschilde</a>, <a href="/user/uid:78397">CA Nana</a>, <a href="/user/uid:1843">SteveLCo</a>, <a href="/user/uid:217457">Laurel in CA</a>, <a href="/user/uid:647166">Dave in Columbus</a>, <a href="/user/uid:127703">Karl Rover</a>, <a href="/user/uid:39394">side pocket</a>, <a href="/user/uid:281939">Had Enough Right Wing BS</a>, <a href="/user/uid:8519">Bob Love</a>, <a href="/user/uid:228792">cwsmoke</a>, <a href="/user/uid:268701">radical simplicity</a>, <a href="/user/uid:98722">aliasalias</a>, <a href="/user/uid:88656">Habitat Vic</a>, <a href="/user/uid:316255">atana</a>, <a href="/user/uid:236087">diggerspop</a>, <a href="/user/uid:329349">BlueEyed In NC</a>, <a href="/user/uid:72100">greenearth</a>, <a href="/user/uid:194338">thomask</a>, <a href="/user/uid:90885">Debs2</a>, <a href="/user/uid:257122">belinda ridgewood</a>, <a href="/user/uid:75321">mbdunn</a>, <a href="/user/uid:104981">GeorgeXVIII</a>, <a href="/user/uid:120115">Calamity Jean</a>, <a href="/user/uid:148551">mkor7</a>, <a href="/user/uid:468656">FrankRose</a>, <a href="/user/uid:120626">RandomNonviolence</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>that it's hard for most people to comprehend.</p>
<p>Let me break it down (and this may end up as a diary if y'all like it).</p>
<p>Consider the case of doomed-to-drown Miami. Its contribution to national GDP was $263 billion in 2010.</p>
<p>A city is land, commerce, and people.</p>
<p>I don't know what Miami real estate is worth. A lot. Billions? It's all going to be abandoned. Ditto its infrastructure - roads, schools, hospitals, drug warehouses, nightclubs and restaurants, malls filled with boutiques selling cute bikinis, etc. All gone.</p>
<p>A few people will try to physically move houses, but not many. Most people will just relocate...where?</p>
<p>Some will cling to the city, moving to higher ground, figuring out canals and kayaks and bridges. But most &nbsp;will leave. Businesses will leave. This contraction will play out over decades, or less if there's a big hurricane, and it will be painful.</p>
<p>I ask people what it costs to abandon Miami, and I get blank stares, shrugs, mumbles "billions," but no one knows where to start that calculation.</p>
<p>The language to calculate what climate change will cost us hasn't been invented yet.</p>
<p>Anyone know what the slow contraction of Detroit from 1950s or 1970s to the bankruptcy has done to the American economy? That will be Miami.</p>
<p>Now, multiply Miami. Over and over again.<br /></p>

