<p>but seeing as I work for a company specializing in filtration, I believe that we could sufficiently filter it relatively cheaply.</p>
<p>The expense would be in the pipelines themselves. &nbsp;To carry enough water to make a difference, they would have to be large and plentiful. If a pipe was 6 feet in diameter then we could expect a flow rate of about 9,000 gallons per second. &nbsp;If the flood lasted one week and at a continuous flow, that would equate to 54 billion gallons of water.</p>
