  <a href="/user/uid:79790">WarrenS</a>, <a href="/user/uid:127703">Karl Rover</a>, <a href="/user/uid:281939">Had Enough Right Wing BS</a>, <a href="/user/uid:8519">Bob Love</a>, <a href="/user/uid:138774">artmartin</a>, <a href="/user/uid:98722">aliasalias</a>, <a href="/user/uid:72100">greenearth</a>, <a href="/user/uid:51040">kamarvt</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>I have an issue with the cost thing though...<br /></p>
<blockquote>cost the equivalent of almost a year's global GDP</blockquote>
I have long argued against people talking about the prohibitive cost of going back to the moon. &nbsp;I argue that going to the moon the first time cost us less than nothing and going back again could save the world from economic destruction.
<p>When we went to the moon, we didn't bundle up all of the money and send it off into space, never to be seen again. &nbsp;The U.S. government spent almost all of the money here in America and that money went to scientists and engineers and workers at NASA and hundreds of other small companies working on contracts who all hired lots of people who all paid taxes and bought things with that money. &nbsp;Probably close to 20% of what the government spent came straight back to America in the form of taxes collected. &nbsp;The majority of the rest was circulated within the economy and created demand of other other products which snowballed helping our economy. &nbsp;</p>
<p>Where we made it less than zero was the advances in technology that were born of necessity because of this endeavor. &nbsp;These technological advances made the United States the world's technology leader for many years to come. &nbsp;We were without a doubt, a world economic superpower in spite of supposed high taxes and high government spending in Vietnam and on NASA.</p>
<p>If we have the catastrophic conditions you suggest (and I believe that we may very well see) it would not cost the world anything economically. &nbsp;We have a choice here on earth to pay for it now and prevent the suffering or pay for it later and do it in spite of the suffering. &nbsp;Just like any disaster, we may not think we have any money in this country but I guarantee you if Russia attacked us, we would find enough money to go to war tomorrow without anyone even bringing up the budget. &nbsp;</p>
<p>No matter when we spend the money, now or later, it will create jobs, stimulate the economy and not cost the American Government anything as long as they hire American workers and then learn from the technology that is created.</p>

  </div>
