  <div class="ct">
  
<p><strong>years ago,</strong> according to a 2008 "genographic" study of mitochondrial DNA. The DNA record indicates that <em>Homo Sapiens</em> was reduced to as few as 2,000 individuals.</p>
<p>The geological record suggests massive droughts in Africa in the preceding period confined our ancestors to isolated pockets of viable habitat. Yet, as the climate became more benign, it only took 10,000 years for our numbers to rebound and the migration out of Africa to begin.</p>
<p>I'm convinced that our genes will survive any future catastrophe. But there are 6.6 billion of us now... the die-off is going to be ugly indeed.</p>
<p>We will survive, but many less adaptable species are going to go extinct: Gorillas, elephants, tigers, whales... Our descendents may mourn their loss, but it's unlikely that they will live in a society that cannot afford sentimentality of any kind.</p>
<p>It isn't human survival we're fighting for... It's the idea of civilization that we've been trying perfect since Plato and Confucius. It's the compassion for our fellow humans that we've tried to uphold since Buddha and Jesus; It's the "liberal" society that we've been struggling toward since Locke and Rousseau.</p>
<p>That's what we'll lose if we crash the biosphere.</p>
<p>But humanity itself will survive.</p>
